'''Ozu Shrine''' (おづじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} in {{jalink|Moriyama|Q857225}}, {{jalink|Shiga Prefecture|Q131358}}.

=== Precinct ===
It stands in a forest 4.3 km northwest of {{jalink|Moriyama Station (Shiga)|Q1042787|Moriyama Station}}<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.biwako-visitors.jp/spot/detail/168|title=Ozu Shrine | Shiga tourism information|accessdate=2020-04-15|publisher=Biwako Visitors Bureau}}</ref>. The shrine lies at the center of Sugie, a settlement that was a key point for transport on Lake Biwa waterways{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. The precinct area is 28,000 {{jalink|square meters|Q25343}}, with the honden standing amid old trees<ref name=":0" />.

=== History ===
The shrine originally worshiped the ancient local Ozu clan; later {{jalink|Ukanomitama|Q3080728|Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto}} became the principal deity<ref name=":0" />. Shrine records say that in {{jalink|567|Q32555}} the shrine buildings were washed out into {{jalink|Lake Biwa|Q200239}} by flood<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.shiga-jinjacho.jp/ycBBS/Board.cgi/02_jinja_db/db/ycDB_02jinja-pc-detail.html?mode:view=1&view:oid=450|title=Shrine introduction: Ozu Shrine (OZU)|accessdate=2020-04-15|publisher=Shiga Prefecture Shrine Office}}</ref>. The dance dedicated by parishioners when welcoming back the divine spirit that had flowed into the lake is said to have become the later Naginata festival<ref>{{Cite book|和書|title=Moriyama City Bulletin|date=2000-05-01|year=2000|publisher=Moriyama City|url=http://www2.city.moriyama.lg.jp/koho/000501/index3.html|accessdate=2020-04-15|page=3}}</ref>. In {{jalink|Bun'ō|Q1199883}} 1 ({{jalink|1260|Q5508}}), offerings from Sagami-no-kami and Echigo-no-kami and donations of Azumigawa fishing grounds were made<ref name=":1" />. Revered by the imperial court and warrior houses, in {{jalink|1335|Q6011}} ({{jalink|Kenmu|Q1193970|Kenmu}} 2) Ashikaga Takauji prohibited armed troops from entering the sacred precinct<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":0" />. The honden burned in the {{jalink|Ōnin War|Q385676}}, then was rebuilt by {{jalink|Rokkaku Takayori|Q2890348}}<ref name=":1" />. It burned again in {{jalink|1505|Q6153}} ({{jalink|Eishō|Q1193577}} 2) during the Eishō disturbances, but the current honden was rebuilt over 18 years by the Enryakuji monk Myōshunbō Jikkan<ref name=":1" />.

In the {{jalink|Edo period|Q184963}}, it had 13 nearby villages as ujiko{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
Its principal deity is Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto; later {{jalink|Susanoo|Q272993|Susanoo-no-Mikoto}} and {{jalink|Kamiōichi-hime|Q11588867|Ōichi-hime-no-Mikoto}} were enshrined as associated deities<ref name=":1" />.

=== Festival ===
Naginata dance is performed every {{jalink|May 5|Q2550}}<ref name=":0" /> and is designated a national {{jalink|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|Q6573893}}<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.biwako-visitors.jp/event/detail/118|title=Naginata-furi (Ozu Shrine) | Shiga tourism information|accessdate=2020-04-15|publisher=Biwako Visitors Bureau}}</ref>. With mikoshi procession, ritual performances are dedicated by rotating duty groups of carriers and dancers{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. In years when Sugie, Akanoi, Yajima, Miyake, Yamaga, and Ishida serve as dance groups, offerings include naginata-furi and Sanyare dance{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. Naginata-furi leads the parade while swinging naginata; Sanyare dancers follow in flower-hat costume with {{jalink|taiko|Q11404}}, {{jalink|kane|Q3482784}}, {{jalink|sasara}}, and {{jalink|flute|Q11405}}{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. Three large mikoshi and two children's mikoshi travel round-trip to {{jalink|Ozu Wakamiya Shrine}} in Akanoi about 1 km away<ref name=":2" />.

Such dances are called {{jalink|fūryū odori|Q11665528}} and are said to have spread from Kyoto across Shiga in the early modern period{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}.

=== Cultural properties ===
[[ファイル:Statue of Ukanomitama at Ozu-jinja.jpg|thumb|Wooden seated Ukanomitama statue (Important Cultural Property)]]
=== Important Cultural Property ===
* Wooden seated statue of Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto
: The goddess statue enshrined in the honden is estimated to date from the mid-{{jalink|Heian period|Q193292}} and is designated {{jalink|Important Cultural Property|Q1188622}}{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. It is a painted wooden image about 50 cm high with a lotus crown, left hand holding a jewel on a raised left knee<ref name=":0" />. It is counted among three deity statues together with examples at {{jalink|Matsuo Taisha|Q710302}} and {{jalink|Yakushi-ji|Q945913}}<ref name=":0" />.

=== Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property ===
* Ōmi Kenketo festival naginata-furi

