'''Ozu Shrine''' (おづじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Moriyama|Q857225|WD=Q857225|1=Moriyama, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}.

=== Precinct ===
It stands in a forest 4.3 km northwest of {{ill|lt=Moriyama Station (Shiga)|Q1042787|WD=Q1042787|lt=Moriyama Station|1=Moriyama Station (Shiga)}}<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.biwako-visitors.jp/spot/detail/168|title=Ozu Shrine | Shiga tourism information|accessdate=2020-04-15|publisher=Biwako Visitors Bureau}}</ref>. The shrine lies at the center of Sugie, a settlement that was a key point for transport on Lake Biwa waterways{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. The precinct area is 28,000 {{ill|lt=square meters|Q25343|WD=Q25343|1=Square metre}}, with the honden standing amid old trees<ref name=":0" />.

=== History ===
The shrine originally worshiped the ancient local Ozu clan; later {{ill|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|1=Ukanomitama}} became the principal deity<ref name=":0" />. Shrine records say that in {{ill|lt=567|Q32555|WD=Q32555|1=567}} the shrine buildings were washed out into {{ill|lt=Lake Biwa|Q200239|WD=Q200239|1=Lake Biwa}} by flood<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|和書|url=http://www.shiga-jinjacho.jp/ycBBS/Board.cgi/02_jinja_db/db/ycDB_02jinja-pc-detail.html?mode:view=1&view:oid=450|title=Shrine introduction: Ozu Shrine (OZU)|accessdate=2020-04-15|publisher=Shiga Prefecture Shrine Office}}</ref>. The dance dedicated by parishioners when welcoming back the divine spirit that had flowed into the lake is said to have become the later Naginata festival<ref>{{Cite book|和書|title=Moriyama City Bulletin|date=2000-05-01|year=2000|publisher=Moriyama City|url=http://www2.city.moriyama.lg.jp/koho/000501/index3.html|accessdate=2020-04-15|page=3}}</ref>. In {{ill|lt=Bun'ō|Q1199883|WD=Q1199883|1=Bun'ō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1260|Q5508|WD=Q5508|1=1260}}), offerings from Sagami-no-kami and Echigo-no-kami and donations of Azumigawa fishing grounds were made<ref name=":1" />. Revered by the imperial court and warrior houses, in {{ill|lt=1335|Q6011|WD=Q6011|1=1335}} ({{ill|lt=Kenmu|Q1193970|WD=Q1193970|lt=Kenmu|1=Kenmu}} 2) Ashikaga Takauji prohibited armed troops from entering the sacred precinct<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":0" />. The honden burned in the {{ill|lt=Ōnin War|Q385676|WD=Q385676|1=Ōnin War}}, then was rebuilt by {{ill|lt=Rokkaku Takayori|Q2890348|WD=Q2890348|1=Rokkaku Takayori}}<ref name=":1" />. It burned again in {{ill|lt=1505|Q6153|WD=Q6153|1=1505}} ({{ill|lt=Eishō|Q1193577|WD=Q1193577|1=Eishō (Muromachi period)}} 2) during the Eishō disturbances, but the current honden was rebuilt over 18 years by the Enryakuji monk Myōshunbō Jikkan<ref name=":1" />.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it had 13 nearby villages as ujiko{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
Its principal deity is Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto; later {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}} and {{ill|lt=Kamiōichi-hime|Q11588867|WD=Q11588867|lt=Ōichi-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Kamuo Ichihime}} were enshrined as associated deities<ref name=":1" />.

=== Festival ===
Naginata dance is performed every {{ill|lt=May 5|Q2550|WD=Q2550|1=May 5}}<ref name=":0" /> and is designated a national {{ill|lt=Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|Q6573893|WD=Q6573893|1=National Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property}}<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|和書|url=https://www.biwako-visitors.jp/event/detail/118|title=Naginata-furi (Ozu Shrine) | Shiga tourism information|accessdate=2020-04-15|publisher=Biwako Visitors Bureau}}</ref>. With mikoshi procession, ritual performances are dedicated by rotating duty groups of carriers and dancers{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. In years when Sugie, Akanoi, Yajima, Miyake, Yamaga, and Ishida serve as dance groups, offerings include naginata-furi and Sanyare dance{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. Naginata-furi leads the parade while swinging naginata; Sanyare dancers follow in flower-hat costume with {{ill|lt=taiko|Q11404|WD=Q11404|1=Drum}}, {{ill|lt=kane|Q3482784|WD=Q3482784|1=Shōko (instrument)}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=sasara|1=UNKNOWN}}, and {{ill|lt=flute|Q11405|WD=Q11405|1=Flute}}{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. Three large mikoshi and two children's mikoshi travel round-trip to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ozu Wakamiya Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} in Akanoi about 1 km away<ref name=":2" />.

Such dances are called {{ill|lt=fūryū odori|Q11665528|WD=Q11665528|1=Furyū-odori}} and are said to have spread from Kyoto across Shiga in the early modern period{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}.

=== Cultural properties ===
[[ファイル:Statue of Ukanomitama at Ozu-jinja.jpg|thumb|Wooden seated Ukanomitama statue (Important Cultural Property)]]
=== Important Cultural Property ===
* Wooden seated statue of Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto
: The goddess statue enshrined in the honden is estimated to date from the mid-{{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} and is designated {{ill|lt=Important Cultural Property|Q1188622|WD=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}}{{Sfn|滋賀県教育委員会事務局文化財保護課|2019|p=184}}. It is a painted wooden image about 50 cm high with a lotus crown, left hand holding a jewel on a raised left knee<ref name=":0" />. It is counted among three deity statues together with examples at {{ill|lt=Matsuo Taisha|Q710302|WD=Q710302|1=Matsunoo Taisha}} and {{ill|lt=Yakushi-ji|Q945913|WD=Q945913|1=Yakushi-ji}}<ref name=":0" />.

=== Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property ===
* Ōmi Kenketo festival naginata-furi

